Big O Notation

Big O notation is used to measure the efficiency of an algorithm by describing how its execution time grows as the input size increases.

Examples:

O(1) → Constant Time
O(log n) → Logarithmic Time
O(n) → Linear Time
O(n²) → Quadratic Time

It helps compare algorithms and predict performance for large datasets.

Search Scenarios
Linear Search
Best Case: O(1)
Element found at first position.
Average Case: O(n)
Element found in middle.
Worst Case: O(n)
Element found at last position or not found.
Binary Search
Best Case: O(1)
Element found at middle.
Average Case: O(log n)
Worst Case: O(log n)
